Bottleneck two — shuffling.

The symptom in the interface is a stage whose time is dominated by shuffle write and shuffle read, with total shuffle write running into hundreds of gigabytes. The network is the bottleneck.

The diagnosis is that joins and aggregations require all rows for a given key to land on the same executor, and that redistribution across the network is the shuffle.

The remedies, in priority order. Broadcast when one side fits in memory. Filter and project early — the smallest shuffle is one that moves the fewest bytes, so push your where and select upstream so the shuffle only carries what's needed. Right-size the shuffle-partitions setting — for a one-terabyte shuffle, two hundred partitions makes each one five gigabytes, which is too big and spills, whereas four thousand partitions puts each at around two-fifty megabytes, the sweet spot. Let adaptive execution coalesce tiny post-shuffle partitions into right-sized ones automatically. And avoid unnecessary repartitioning — calling repartition right before a join, when the optimiser was going to shuffle correctly anyway, just buys you a second shuffle.
